{"text": "further discussed under Special topics in the lecture regarding Quantum states, operations and measurements . The\n\npresentation of the Master Equation formalism for a system that is coupled to a bath has been di\u000bered to Lecture\n\nNotes in Statistical Mechanics and Mesoscopic , arXiv:1107.0568\n\n101\n\n[20] The cross section in the Born approximation\n\n= = = = = = [20.1] Cross Section\n\nIn both classical mechanics and quantum mechanics there are two types of problems: closed systems and open systems.\n\nWe will discuss an open system. The dynamical problem that we will analyze is called a \"scattering problem\". For\n\nexample, a wave that is scattered on a sphere. In a problem of this type the energy is given. We assume that there\n\nis an \"incident particle \rux\" and we ask what is the \"scattered \rux\".\n\nshadow\n\nWe notice that the sphere \"hides\" a certain area of the beam. The total hidden area is called the \"total cross\n\nsection\"\u001btotal. Let us assume that we have a beam of particles with energy Eand velocity vE, so that the current\n\ndensity is:\n\nJ[particles/time/area] = \u001a0vE (20.1)\n\nwhere\u001a0is the particle density. We write the scattered current as:\n\nIscattered = [\u001btotal]\u0002J (20.2)\n\nwhere the cross section \u001btotal is de\n\nned as the ratio of the scattered current Iscattered to the incident particle \rux\n\ndensityJ. We notice that each area element of the sphere scatters to a di\u000berent direction. Therefore, it is more\n\ninteresting to talk about the di\u000berential cross section \u001b(\n\n). In full analogy \u001b(\n\n)d\n\nis de\n\nned by the formula:\n\nI(k2d\n\njk0) = [\u001b(\n\n)d\n\n]\u0002J (20.3)\n\nwherek0denotes the initial momentum, while kis the\n\nnal momentum. Here only the scattering into the angular\n\nelementd\n\nis detected.\n\n= = = = = = [20.2] Cross section and rate of transition\n\nFor the theoretical discussion that will follow, it is convenient to think of the space as if it has a\n\nnite volume\n\nL3=LxLyLzwith periodic boundary conditions.", "embedding": [-0.015563633, -0.010298375, 0.031357188, -0.03546279, -0.009045619, -0.01094266, -0.00807622, -0.0039908453, -0.04233262, 0.07816445, 0.05518318, 0.040518846, 0.016805617, 0.014938179, -0.042521507, 0.04581285, -0.030219905, -0.011015575, -0.11688316, 0.00688001, 0.0016468678, -0.00034381537, -0.06737585, -0.0072237058, -0.037132986, 0.0109099215, 0.03215439, 0.01570657, 0.033208434, 0.04552079, 0.010855388, -0.013326028, -0.011964178, -0.03697126, 0.034172818, -0.016822945, 0.02888776, -0.04873619, -0.001333674, -0.06230412, 0.025035406, 0.009864738, 0.020764917, -0.024112748, -0.017173786, -0.005075467, -0.022271654, 0.0038720893, -0.0339068, -0.038947795, 0.043403465, -0.01417731, -0.016266765, -0.0460099, 0.006870415, 0.0069978395, 0.001972512, 0.029893722, -0.033671465, 0.0018896916, 0.05345308, -0.0147465365, -0.0070486427, -0.059244484, 0.014320048, 0.058079224, -0.028482763, 0.011657599, 0.025156276, -0.013118191, -0.030475764, -0.019759633, 0.018661475, 0.011878417, -0.017921524, 0.041344877, 0.033379234, -0.014667458, -0.050233927, -0.014439214, 0.0032662535, -0.01736188, -0.038802538, 0.018406468, -0.009139088, -0.0029955066, 0.008268521, -0.01050158, 0.0053558974, 0.005826682, 0.03280362, 0.05675914, -0.008592695, 0.0058765826, 0.0019917397, 0.049464174, -0.012899673, 0.019516584, 0.04046597, 0.0027648883, 0.0095169535, 0.06896091, -0.031466674, 0.037567914, -0.01913531, 0.049214847, -0.041261703, 0.030698393, 0.017342119, -0.047249634, 0.018413879, -0.00945632, -0.011361401, 0.020374803, 0.0010790557, 0.017656846, 0.024177972, 0.018522242, -0.019550456, -0.032482546, -0.010485233, 0.025162306, 0.04461984, 0.0015147713, 0.03872865, -0.0052595036, -0.01763188, 0.006586903, -0.054232225, 0.0019299858, -0.00011682501, -0.025226535, -0.008724134, 0.03473018, -0.03521067, 0.009298058, 0.0084451325, 0.032102615, -0.0019345258, -0.028462453, -0.0017456092, -0.02046